VALUES ('f78ed180-397c-41dd-a2f5-c665483cf74a', 'Which choice best characterizes the text''s rhetorical structure?', 'Historians examining trade route 100010 note that camel caravans carried not only goods but also astronomical tables, spreading navigation techniques across deserts long before printed maps existed. Merchants who survived the crossing depended on star charts copied onto leather scrolls, and those copies often accumulated marginal notes from later travelers. A ledger recovered near route 100010 lists dates, caravan leaders, and the scientific texts exchanged at each oasis, suggesting that commerce and scholarship moved together. When one city tightened tariffs, caravans rerouted through secondary wells, and the astronomical knowledge rerouted with them. Recently, however, investigators published findings that complicate the long-standing consensus described above. Modern', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"It claims effects are analyzed before causes are defined, inverting the passage''s movement from causal mechanism to documented outcome in the study described in context as written overall in sum in context.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Partial Scope] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops."},{"id":"B","text":"It establishes a cause-and-effect claim, supplies seasonal field evidence, and acknowledges limitations before drawing implications as written here throughout overall in sum in context as written in sum in context as written.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct (B). Correct (B). This choice matches the passage''s rhetorical architecture from framework through evidence to qualified implications."},{"id":"C","text":"It lists technical vocabulary from the opening sentences without showing how those terms support a cumulative argument across the full paragraph from mechanism to outcome here in context as written here throughout.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Narrative Speculation] [Partial